@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson Companies do in fact pay for this service. It is advertisement.I have ran million dollar businesses, and this is a service that is paid for. If some companies get it free, then congrats to them. Maybe take some classes, and educate yourself.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson Too bad that companies and organizations do pay for email blasts. You can send one now because you have what, five contacts? Obviously you can send that straight from gmail. However, a 50,000 client list, you have to pay for that.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson An email blast is paid for, you are paying for a service to email out a list of customers. You can keep stroking your empty head‚Ä¶ Maybe try hooked on phonics or ABC mouse, might be able to help you understand!

@uAEmsx @bradsferguson @axmantim Although word of mouth marketing is a form of advertising, keep in mind that WOM doesn‚Äôt represent an ad or ads. Far from it, actually. In most cases, word of mouth is totally free. Organic conversations, feedback and reviews can‚Äôt quite literally be bought.

@uAEmsx @bradsferguson @axmantim There are connections yes, a marketing team will design advertisements, etc. however, there are some in this thread who seem to think they are one in the same, and are unable to see the differences.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson An advertisement would be an outside publication drawing someone to the companies website. An email blast is an ad, a newspaper has ads, magazines, billboards, bus benches‚Ä¶ even modern advertisements like PAYING to have your website show up first on google.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson Their website wouldn‚Äôt be considered advertisement because they are not loosing any financial revenue in having any promotion on their own site. And since I taught you the definition of advertisement, (refresher - it is a paid announcement) therefore website not an advertisement.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson They may not pay Chas for the space, but by them using the space, they are losing revenue from another company who would pay to use the space. That loss is payment for advertisement. They do not have advertisements on their own website.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson I think you are the one who is delusional. They are in theory paying for an advertisement on their console because it is replacing what would be an advertisement for another product, whether it be a game or what ever they are promoting.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson You are correct though, when Sony or Microsoft put something on their platforms, that is an advertisement. Went? Because they PAY to use that space. Again returning to the definition of advertisement, they are PAYING to promote goods or services.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson I‚Äôm starting to think your just uneducated. A job posting is a posting not an advertisement. If a company PAYS to have their posting seen before other postings , that is in fact an advertisement.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson That is literally the definition from the dictionary. I‚Äôm not sure where you went to school, but I‚Äôd ask for a refund, or at least a refresher. Advertisements are paid for, not just just created by an employee. An advertisement is paying another company to promote your company.

@axmantim @bradsferguson Tesla doesn‚Äôt use advertisements. Yes they pay people for marketing, that‚Äôs what companies do. I worked in the marketing field, it‚Äôs not the same as advertisements. Again, look up what an advertisement is and maybe your foggy brain will be cleared up.

@axmantim @uAEmsx @bradsferguson I think you are the one who needs to look the definition up. Here I‚Äôll help- a paid announcement, as of goods for sale, in newspapers or magazines, on radio or television, or on the internet. So again, Tesla doesn‚Äôt make any paid announcements.

@uAEmsx @bradsferguson @axmantim Ads and marketing though are connected doesn‚Äôt make them the same. American Football and European Football share a name, doesn‚Äôt make them the same. When you meet someone new, you may act different, that‚Äôs you marketing yourself how you want to be perceived.

@axmantim @bradsferguson So if I said I like my Tesla, then I am now an advertisement for Tesla? I think that only furthers this gentleman‚Äôs point. Tesla got where it is today with free advertisement. Marketing team or not, Tesla doesn‚Äôt need commercials in the super bowl or stadiums named after them.
